<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="53" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="53">
Native to the Palaearctic region. Widespread in Europe, also recorded from North Africa and Caucasus (
<bibRefCitation author="Daffner, H" journalOrPublisher="Folia Entomologica Hungarica" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" pagination="9 - 163" refId="B41" refString="Daffner, H, 1983. Revision der palaearktischen Arten der Tribus Leiodini Leach (Coleoptera, Leiodidae). Folia Entomologica Hungarica 44: 9 - 163" title="Revision der palaearktischen Arten der Tribus Leiodini Leach (Coleoptera, Leiodidae)." volume="44" year="1983">Daffner 1983</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Perreau, M" editor="Loebl, I" journalOrPublisher="Canadian Journal of Arthropod Identification" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" refId="B169" refString="Perreau, M, Loebl, I, Smetana, A, 2004. Leiodidae. In: LoeblISmetanaA (Eds) Catalogue of Palaearctic Coleoptera (Vol.2). Apollo Books, Stenstrup, 133-203." title="Leiodidae. In: LoeblISmetanaA (Eds) Catalogue of Palaearctic Coleoptera (Vol. 2). Apollo Books, Stenstrup, 133 - 203." year="2004">Perreau 2004</bibRefCitation>
). Adventive in the Nearctic region (Ontario, Canada).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="53" type="canadian records">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Canadian records.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Ontario: Puslinch Township, 15-Aug-2010 to 22-Aug-2010 (1 ex, CBG); Guelph, 18-Aug-2010 (1 ex, CBG).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="53" type="diagnostic information">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Diagnostic information</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="53">
(based on 
<bibRefCitation author="Daffner, H" journalOrPublisher="Folia Entomologica Hungarica" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" pagination="9 - 163" refId="B41" refString="Daffner, H, 1983. Revision der palaearktischen Arten der Tribus Leiodini Leach (Coleoptera, Leiodidae). Folia Entomologica Hungarica 44: 9 - 163" title="Revision der palaearktischen Arten der Tribus Leiodini Leach (Coleoptera, Leiodidae)." volume="44" year="1983">Daffner 1983</bibRefCitation>
). Body length 2.2-4 mm. Habitus as in 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Leiodes polita (Marsham) A habitus L. Borowiec B male left metafemur, dorsal view C aedeagus, ventral view D aedeagus, lateral view. Scale bars: 1.0 mm (A), 0.5 mm (B), 0.2 mm (C, D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.894.37862.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/362138" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.894.37862.figure2">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
. Red-brown or yellow-brown, head, pronotum and the sutural and lateral margins of elytra sometimes darkened. Antennae long, with a strongly transverse, darkened club, last antennomere narrower than antennomere 10. Head normally with four punctures in transverse series. Basal margin of pronotum sinuate laterally. Mesoventrite with a long, low and evenly curved medial carina, not reaching the transverse carina and without excavation anteriorly. Metaventrite approximately as long as abdominal ventrites 1 and 2 combined. Elytra with regular, strongly and densely punctate striae, interstitial punctures sparse. Elytra not transversely strigose or strongly microsculptured. Elytral stria 9 separated from side margin at basal third, forming a subhumeral row of punctures. Protibiae only moderately widened towards apex. Metafemora in both sexes with an apical projection at both inner and outer margins, projections stronger in males (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Leiodes polita (Marsham) A habitus L. Borowiec B male left metafemur, dorsal view C aedeagus, ventral view D aedeagus, lateral view. Scale bars: 1.0 mm (A), 0.5 mm (B), 0.2 mm (C, D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.894.37862.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/362138" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.894.37862.figure2">Fig. 2B</figureCitation>
). Male metatibiae bent inward starting from the basal third. Male genitalia as in 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Leiodes polita (Marsham) A habitus L. Borowiec B male left metafemur, dorsal view C aedeagus, ventral view D aedeagus, lateral view. Scale bars: 1.0 mm (A), 0.5 mm (B), 0.2 mm (C, D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.894.37862.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/362138" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.894.37862.figure2">Fig. 2C, D</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="53" type="bionomic notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Bionomic notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="53">
This eurytopic species is found in forests, forest edges, heaths, gardens etc. in Europe (
<bibRefCitation author="Koch, K" journalOrPublisher="Goecke &amp; Evers Verlag, Krefeld" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" refId="B115" refString="Koch, K, 1989b. Die Kaefer Mitteleuropas, Oekologie (Vol. 2). Goecke &amp; Evers Verlag, Krefeld" title="Die Kaefer Mitteleuropas, Oekologie (Vol. 2)." year="1989 b">Koch 1989b</bibRefCitation>
). The Canadian specimens were collected with Malaise traps in suburban residential areas in southern Ontario.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
